From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: gregordinary <33880035+gregordinary@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Tue, 30 Jun 2026 12:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] rocket: couple NPU rail voltage to the compute clock (f/V
 coupling)

Companion to the rocket_npu_clk_hz clock lever (apply AFTER it). When that param
raises the NPU compute clock, scale vdd_npu_s0 with it so a fast clock never runs
at a low voltage -- the V/f-marginal state that hard-locked the box at 900 MHz.
BL31 sets only the PLL and never the rail, so if Linux does not couple V to f,
nothing does.

At the validated 600 MHz operating point this is a literal no-op:
npu_uv_for_hz(600 MHz) returns the 0.80 V floor, which is where the rail already
sits. It is insurance for going ABOVE 600 MHz, which is not currently worth it
(no measured speedup, and a pinned 900 MHz hard-locks the box). Take it if you
intend to explore that range; skip it and the clock lever alone is complete and
correct.

Design: hold the regulator for the device lifetime (the framework aggregates LIVE
consumers by max, so a put would drop our vote); raise V before clock on resume,
lower clock before V on suspend; a 0.80 V floor pins the rail at today's voltage
at <=600 MHz and prevents our own vote from ever undervolting the shared rail.
Default (rocket_npu_uv=0) uses the vendor f->V map with that floor. Degrades to
clock-only if no npu-supply; -EPROBE_DEFER from the supply get is propagated
rather than collapsing permanently to clock-only.

On a clk_set_rate failure after the voltage was raised, roll the rail back to the
idle floor before propagating the error, so a failed resume never strands the rail
high at the stock clock.

The voltage path is deliberately PER core and is NOT refcounted the way the shared
clock's park is. The rail only actually falls once every core has lowered its own
request -- exactly what max-aggregation gives us. Gating it on the last core down
would strand the earlier cores' requests high and the rail would never come down
at all.
---
 drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.c |  21 +++++
 drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.h |  11 +++
 drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c  | 128 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++--
 3 files changed, 154 insertions(+), 6 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.c b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.c
index 66501861e..5d3879674 100644
--- a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.c
+++ b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.c
@@ -9,6 +9,7 @@
 #include <linux/iommu.h>
 #include <linux/platform_device.h>
 #include <linux/pm_runtime.h>
+#include <linux/regulator/consumer.h>
 #include <linux/reset.h>
 
 #include "rocket_core.h"
@@ -51,6 +52,26 @@ int rocket_core_init(struct rocket_core *core)
 		core->npu_clk = NULL;
 	}
 
+	/*
+	 * Acquire the NPU rail (DT "npu-supply" = vdd_npu_s0) once, for the
+	 * device lifetime, so the voltage vote we cast when the clock is raised
+	 * persists (see struct rocket_core / rocket_drv.c). The rail is also
+	 * pd_npu's domain-supply, so the genpd enables it -- we never enable it
+	 * here, only scale its voltage. Optional: a board without the supply
+	 * just runs clock-only, never failing to probe -- mirroring the "degrade,
+	 * don't disrupt" rule of the clock path. -EPROBE_DEFER (the PMIC has not
+	 * probed yet) is the one error we propagate, so the supply is retried
+	 * rather than silently and permanently collapsed to clock-only.
+	 */
+	core->npu_supply = devm_regulator_get_optional(dev, "npu");
+	if (IS_ERR(core->npu_supply)) {
+		if (PTR_ERR(core->npu_supply) == -EPROBE_DEFER)
+			return PTR_ERR(core->npu_supply);
+		dev_info(dev, "rocket: no \"npu\" supply (%ld); NPU voltage scaling disabled\n",
+			 PTR_ERR(core->npu_supply));
+		core->npu_supply = NULL;
+	}
+
 	core->pc_iomem = devm_platform_ioremap_resource_byname(pdev, "pc");
 	if (IS_ERR(core->pc_iomem)) {
 		dev_err(dev, "couldn't find PC registers %ld\n", PTR_ERR(core->pc_iomem));
diff --git a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.h b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.h
index 1080f3b30..10e89621f 100644
--- a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.h
+++ b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.h
@@ -12,6 +12,8 @@
 
 #include "rocket_registers.h"
 
+struct regulator;
+
 #define rocket_pc_readl(core, reg) \
 	readl((core)->pc_iomem + (REG_PC_##reg))
 #define rocket_pc_writel(core, reg, value) \
@@ -49,6 +51,15 @@ struct rocket_core {
 	 */
 	struct clk *npu_clk;
 
+	/*
+	 * vdd_npu_s0 rail (DT "npu-supply"); held for the device lifetime so our
+	 * voltage vote persists (the regulator framework aggregates LIVE
+	 * consumers by max -- dropping the handle would drop the vote). Scaled
+	 * with the compute clock by the rocket_npu_clk_hz path; NULL when no
+	 * supply is wired (then we run clock-only). See rocket_drv.c.
+	 */
+	struct regulator *npu_supply;
+
 	struct iommu_group *iommu_group;
 
 	struct mutex job_lock;
diff --git a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c
index 3dd6536a7..aa1c2d675 100644
--- a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c
+++ b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c
@@ -13,6 +13,7 @@
 #include <linux/of.h>
 #include <linux/platform_device.h>
 #include <linux/pm_runtime.h>
+#include <linux/regulator/consumer.h>
 
 #include "rocket_device.h"
 #include "rocket_drv.h"
@@ -59,6 +60,56 @@ module_param(rocket_npu_clk_hz, ulong, 0644);
 MODULE_PARM_DESC(rocket_npu_clk_hz,
 	"NPU compute clock target in Hz applied in runtime-resume (e.g. 600000000); 0 = stock 200 MHz");
 
+/*
+ * NPU rail (vdd_npu_s0) voltage coupling, applied together with
+ * rocket_npu_clk_hz so a raised clock always gets a matching voltage.
+ *
+ * Floor of 0.80 V: the rail already sits at 0.80 V today, and the regulator
+ * framework aggregates consumers by max -- so voting the floor PINS the rail at
+ * today's voltage (no change at <=600 MHz) and, crucially, prevents our own
+ * vote from ever dropping the shared rail below 0.80 V. The 0.95 V ceiling is
+ * the RK8602 vdd_npu_s0 DT regulator-max. Firmware (BL31) sets only the PLL and
+ * never the voltage, so if Linux does not couple V to f, nothing does -- which
+ * is the V/f-marginal state that hard-locked the box at 900 MHz.
+ */
+#define ROCKET_NPU_VOLT_FLOOR_UV	800000UL	/* proven-stable rail at <=600 MHz */
+#define ROCKET_NPU_VOLT_MAX_UV		950000		/* vdd_npu_s0 ceiling (DT regulator-max) */
+
+/*
+ * Optional fixed override of the NPU rail voltage in microvolts, applied with
+ * rocket_npu_clk_hz. 0 (default) selects the vendor f->V map with the 0.80 V
+ * floor (npu_uv_for_hz()). For future >600 MHz bring-up only; the map+floor
+ * default is what keeps the proven 600 MHz operating point byte-for-byte.
+ */
+static unsigned long rocket_npu_uv;
+module_param(rocket_npu_uv, ulong, 0644);
+MODULE_PARM_DESC(rocket_npu_uv,
+	"NPU rail voltage override in microvolts applied with rocket_npu_clk_hz; 0 = vendor f/V map with 0.80 V floor");
+
+/*
+ * Vendor RK3588 npu_opp_table frequency->voltage points (rockchip-linux 6.6
+ * rk3588s.dtsi): 300-700 MHz -> 0.70 V, 800 -> 0.75 V, 900 -> 0.80 V,
+ * 1000 -> 0.85 V (the vendor never exceeds 0.85 V for the NPU). Returns the
+ * vendor microvolts for a target rate, clamped UP to the 0.80 V floor. The true
+ * per-chip ceiling is OTP PVTPLL, not this table -- this is a conservative safe
+ * map for enabling >600 MHz later; it makes the lever safe, it does not pull it.
+ */
+static unsigned long npu_uv_for_hz(unsigned long hz)
+{
+	unsigned long uv;
+
+	if (hz <= 700000000UL)
+		uv = 700000UL;
+	else if (hz <= 800000000UL)
+		uv = 750000UL;
+	else if (hz <= 900000000UL)
+		uv = 800000UL;
+	else
+		uv = 850000UL;		/* >= 1 GHz */
+
+	return max(uv, ROCKET_NPU_VOLT_FLOOR_UV);
+}
+
 static void
 rocket_iommu_domain_destroy(struct kref *kref)
 {
@@ -293,7 +344,36 @@ static int rocket_device_runtime_resume(struct device *dev)
 	mutex_lock(&rocket_clk_lock);
 
 	if (rocket_npu_clk_hz) {
+		struct regulator *npu_reg = rdev->cores[core].npu_supply;
 		struct clk *npu_clk = rdev->cores[core].npu_clk;
+		bool raised_v = false;
+
+		/*
+		 * Voltage-up BEFORE clock-up. A fast clock at a low voltage is the
+		 * V/f-marginal state that hard-locked the box at 900 MHz, and BL31
+		 * never scales the rail -- so we must raise it here first. The rail
+		 * is the pd_npu domain-supply (already enabled by the genpd), shared
+		 * with the genpd consumer, so we only adjust voltage (no
+		 * regulator_enable) and read back the effective value to confirm the
+		 * request took. With the default 0.80 V floor this is a no-op at
+		 * <=600 MHz (the rail already sits at 0.80 V). On a failed/absent
+		 * regulator we warn and raise the clock anyway -- clock-only is
+		 * exactly today's behaviour, never worse.
+		 */
+		if (npu_reg) {
+			unsigned long uv = rocket_npu_uv ? rocket_npu_uv :
+					   npu_uv_for_hz(rocket_npu_clk_hz);
+			int vr = regulator_set_voltage(npu_reg, uv, ROCKET_NPU_VOLT_MAX_UV);
+
+			if (vr) {
+				dev_warn(dev, "rocket: regulator_set_voltage(npu, %lu uV) failed: %d (clock-only)\n",
+					 uv, vr);
+			} else {
+				raised_v = true;
+				dev_info(dev, "rocket: core %d NPU vdd -> %lu uV (reads back %d uV)\n",
+					 core, uv, regulator_get_voltage(npu_reg));
+			}
+		}
 
 		if (!npu_clk) {
 			dev_warn(dev, "rocket: no \"npu\" clock; cannot apply %lu Hz\n",
@@ -303,14 +383,20 @@ static int rocket_device_runtime_resume(struct device *dev)
 
 			if (r) {
 				/*
-				 * Undo the bulk-clock enable and PROPAGATE the failure: a
-				 * degraded resume must not silently return 0 with the device
-				 * half-programmed. The PM core then leaves the domain
-				 * suspended rather than running at an unintended rate. The
-				 * refcount is NOT taken -- this core never held the rate.
+				 * Clock raise failed AFTER the voltage raise. Roll the rail
+				 * back to the idle floor (never strand it high at the stock
+				 * clock), undo the bulk-clock enable, and PROPAGATE the
+				 * failure: a degraded resume must not silently return 0 with
+				 * the device half-programmed. The PM core then leaves the
+				 * domain suspended rather than running at an unintended rate.
+				 * The refcount is NOT taken -- this core never held the rate.
 				 */
-				dev_warn(dev, "rocket: clk_set_rate(npu, %lu Hz) failed: %d (failing resume)\n",
+				dev_warn(dev, "rocket: clk_set_rate(npu, %lu Hz) failed: %d (reverting voltage, failing resume)\n",
 					 rocket_npu_clk_hz, r);
+				if (raised_v)
+					regulator_set_voltage(npu_reg,
+							      npu_uv_for_hz(ROCKET_NPU_POWER_DOWN_HZ),
+							      ROCKET_NPU_VOLT_MAX_UV);
 				mutex_unlock(&rocket_clk_lock);
 				clk_bulk_disable_unprepare(ARRAY_SIZE(rdev->cores[core].clks),
 							   rdev->cores[core].clks);
@@ -363,10 +449,40 @@ static int rocket_device_runtime_suspend(struct device *dev)
 		rocket_clk_users--;
 
 	if (rocket_npu_clk_hz) {
+		struct regulator *npu_reg = rdev->cores[core].npu_supply;
 		struct clk *npu_clk = rdev->cores[core].npu_clk;
 
 		if (npu_clk && rocket_clk_users == 0)
 			clk_set_rate(npu_clk, ROCKET_NPU_POWER_DOWN_HZ);
+
+		/*
+		 * Clock-down BEFORE voltage-down (mirror of resume). Lower the rail
+		 * to the idle target only AFTER the clock is parked at 200 MHz, so
+		 * the domain never powers off at a rate above its voltage. The idle
+		 * target is the 0.80 V floor (npu_uv_for_hz(200 MHz)) -- we never
+		 * drop below today's voltage. The shared rail aggregates by max, so
+		 * a sibling core still running at a raised rate keeps its voltage.
+		 * A failed lowering is non-fatal (the rail simply stays higher, which
+		 * is the safe direction) but must not be swallowed silently.
+		 *
+		 * This stays PER CORE -- it is deliberately NOT gated on
+		 * rocket_clk_users the way the clock park above is, and must not be.
+		 * The rail only actually falls once EVERY core has lowered its own
+		 * request, which is exactly what the regulator's max-aggregation
+		 * gives us; gating it on the last core would instead leave the
+		 * earlier cores' requests stranded high and the rail would never come
+		 * down at all. It is also safe when we did NOT park the clock above
+		 * (siblings still running): their requests hold the rail at the rate
+		 * they need.
+		 */
+		if (npu_reg) {
+			int vr = regulator_set_voltage(npu_reg,
+						       npu_uv_for_hz(ROCKET_NPU_POWER_DOWN_HZ),
+						       ROCKET_NPU_VOLT_MAX_UV);
+
+			if (vr)
+				dev_warn(dev, "rocket: regulator_set_voltage(npu, idle) failed: %d\n", vr);
+		}
 	}
 
 	mutex_unlock(&rocket_clk_lock);
-- 
2.43.0

